d States, this book makes a major contribution to understanding technology’s role in fostering new forms of migrant sociality and subjectivity. It focuses on the forms of sociality and belonging that these mediations enable, adding to important anthropological debates about affect, subjectivity, and sociality in today’s mobile world. It also makes significant contributions to studies of inequality in Latin America, showcasing the intersection of transnational mobility with structures and processes of exclusion in both national and global contexts. A key resource for understanding the experiences of racialized and indigenous migrant populations, Mobile Selves demonstrates the critical role that ethnography can play in transdisciplinary migration studies and exemplifies what comparative migration studies stand to gain from anthropological analysis and ethnographic methodologies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aPeruvian AmericansxEthnic identity. 0aPeruvian AmericansxSocial conditions. 0aRace awarenesszPeru. 0aRace awarenesszUnited States. 0aTransnationalismxSocial aspectszPeru. 0aTransnationalismxSocial aspectszUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831107289960 cprintz978147980346040uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479803460.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479863778423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479863778/original  a978-3-11-072899-6  New York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPD